properties.description:
...Accumulating Snow Tonight...

.A quick-hitting band of snow moves through the region tonight
and exits before sunrise on Thursday. Widespread snow
accumulations of 1 to 2 inches are expected with two embedded
corridors of higher snow totals where amounts could push 3 to 4
inches. The northern corridor is expected to run from roughly
Mankato, MN northeast to near Wausau, WI while the second band
develops along or just south of Interstate 90 in far southeast
Minnesota and southwest Wisconsin. However, there is uncertainty
in where these two bands exactly set up, which will impact
forecast snow amounts. This snow could lead to slippery travel
overnight and possibly for the Thursday morning commute on any
untreated roads.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 2 to 4 inches.
The snow may come down at rates of over 1 inch per hour for
short periods of time.

* WHERE...Portions of southeast Minnesota and central, north
central and west central Wisconsin.

* WHEN...From 9 PM this evening to 6 AM CST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Some locations with in the advisory may see
less than 2 inches of snow, with the greatest confidence in
these lower snowfall totals running from near Rochester, MN, up
through Black River Falls, WI.
properties.instruction:
Slow down and use caution while traveling.

In Minnesota, visit 511mn.org for road conditions. In Wisconsin,
visit 511wi.gov for road conditions.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 13 at 3:19PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
properties.description:
Strong southerly chinook winds blowing across the Alaska Range
will continue into Wednesday and possibly into Thursday.
Temperatures this morning have risen into the 30s this morning
along many highways across Interior Alaska, with some lower 40s
occuring south of Fairbanks. These warm temperatures will cause
walking and driving surfaces to become slippery. Some valley
locations north and east of Fairbanks will remain below freezing.

Temperatures will remain very warm along the Alaska Range through
Thursday and partial melting of snow and ice may occur, making
travel surfaces more slippery.

Areas further north such as near Fairbanks will likely have hill
top temperatures remain near freezing the next several days,
while valleys will have temperatures fluctuate from near freezing
during the day and back into the teens or single digits at night.
This will cause travel surfaces in hills to become more slippery
over the next several days as snow and ice starts to melt. Valley
locations could get more slippery as well.

NWSheadline: Temperatures Near Freezing The Next Several Days Over The Interior

properties.description:

beginning midday Wednesday, spreading rain/snow mix and snow
across northern and central Nevada. Light valley rain and mountain
snow will be present across most of northern Nevada with snow
levels around 5500-6000 feet. Snowfall amounts of 1-3 inches are
expected across Northern Elko County and 3-6 inches in the Ruby
Mountains and East Humboldt Range Wednesday evening through
Thursday morning. The valley floors for the rest of northern and
central Nevada will see accumulations of less than an inch. West-
southwest winds of 15-20 mph with gusts approaching 35-40 mph
will be situated over the ridge lines and higher terrain, leading
to blowing and drifting snow. Drier conditions are expected for
the rest of the day Thursday as the storm system exits the region.

Visit www.weather.gov/elko for the latest weather information.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 13 at 11:45AM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
properties.description:
Strong southerly chinook winds blowing across the Alaska Range
will continue into Wednesday and possibly into Thursday.
Temperatures this morning have risen into the 30s this morning
along many highways across Interior Alaska, with some lower 40s
occuring south of Fairbanks. These warm temperatures will cause
walking and driving surfaces to become slippery. Some valley
locations north and east of Fairbanks will remain below freezing.

Temperatures will remain very warm along the Alaska Range through
Thursday and partial melting of snow and ice may occur, making
travel surfaces more slippery.

Areas further north such as near Fairbanks will likely have hill
top temperatures remain near freezing the next several days,
while valleys will have temperatures fluctuate from near freezing
during the day and back into the teens or single digits at night.
This will cause travel surfaces in hills to become more slippery
over the next several days as snow and ice starts to melt. Valley
locations could get more slippery as well.

THE FOLLOWING MESSAGE IS TRANSMITTED AT THE REQUEST OF THE
GALLATIN NATIONAL FOREST AVALANCHE CENTER.

AVALANCHE WARNING

The Gallatin National Forest Avalanche Center is issuing a
Backcountry Avalanche Warning for the Bridger Range near Bozeman.
New and wind-drifted snow overloaded an exceptionally weak
snowpack, creating very dangerous avalanche conditions. Natural
and human-triggered avalanches are likely. Avoid avalanche
terrain and avalanche runout zones. The avalanche danger is HIGH
on all slopes. Contact the Gallatin National Forest Avalanche
Center for more detailed information.

Website: www.mtavalanche.com

Avalanche Hotline: 406-587-6981

This warning will expire or be updated by 6:00 a.m. on Wednesday,
February 14th.

properties.areaDesc: Northern Seward Peninsula; Interior Seward Peninsula; St Lawrence Island
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 2:14PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
properties.description:
A strong low pressure system will bring a large amount of warm
and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Wednesday.
Areas can expect a mix of snow and freezing rain with this system
as it moves north. Freezing rain chances will reach as far north
as Kivalina by Tuesday afternoon. Ice accumulations of up to one
tenth of an inch are possible, with snow amounts ranging from 2
to 5 inches where Winter Storm Warnings are not in effect. Higher
snow totals are likely in the Bendeleben Mountains and where
warnings are in effect.

The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high
as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from
Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels
to rise 1 to 2 feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and
Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these
strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice
making travel difficult.

Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at
www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.

NWSheadline: Strong Winds And Mixed Precipitation Early This Week
